      'OAuth 2.0 is the industry-standard authorization framework that enables applications to obtain limited access to user accounts on third-party services without exposing credentials. OAuth 2.0 defines authorization flows (grant types) including Authorization Code with PKCE for web and mobile apps, Client Credentials for server-to-server communication, and Device Authorization for IoT devices. OpenID Connect (OIDC) extends OAuth 2.0 with an identity layer for authentication.\n\nImplementing OAuth correctly requires understanding authorization servers, resource servers, client types (confidential vs public), scopes, tokens (access tokens, refresh tokens, ID tokens), and security considerations. Identity providers like Auth0, Okta, Keycloak, and Firebase Authentication provide managed OAuth implementations, while libraries in every major language simplify custom implementations.\n\nOAuth 2.1 consolidates best practices from OAuth 2.0 security updates, mandating PKCE for all clients, prohibiting the implicit grant, and requiring exact redirect URI matching. Understanding OAuth security threats—token theft, redirect URI manipulation, CSRF attacks, and scope escalation—is essential for building secure authentication systems. Modern implementations leverage tokens stored in HTTP-only cookies and short-lived access tokens with refresh token rotation.',
