    slug: 'jwt-authentication',
    title: 'JWT Authentication',
    category: 'technical',
    description:
      'JSON Web Tokens (JWT) are a compact, URL-safe means of representing claims to be transferred between two parties. JWTs are widely used for authentication and authorization in web applications, API security, and microservices communication. A JWT consists of three parts: a header specifying the algorithm, a payload containing claims (user data, permissions, expiration), and a signature ensuring the token has not been tampered with.\n\nJWT-based authentication works by issuing a signed token upon successful login, which the client includes in subsequent requests via the Authorization header. The server validates the signature and extracts claims without querying a database, enabling stateless authentication. HMAC-SHA256 (HS256) and RSA-SHA256 (RS256) are the most common signing algorithms, with RS256 preferred for distributed systems where the private key stays with the issuer.\n\nBest practices include short-lived access tokens (15-30 minutes), refresh token rotation for session extension, HTTP-only cookies for browser storage to prevent XSS attacks, token blacklisting for forced logout, and proper claim validation. JWTs should never store sensitive data in the payload since it is Base64-encoded (not encrypted) and readable by anyone with the token.',
    whyImportant:
      'JWT is the most common token format for web application authentication and is required knowledge for backend and full-stack developers. Understanding JWT implementation, security implications, and best practices is essential for building secure applications. JWT appears in virtually every modern web application architecture.\n\nDemonstrating JWT expertise shows employers you understand stateless authentication, token-based security, and the trade-offs between different authentication strategies. This knowledge is critical for roles involving API security, microservices authentication, and user session management.',
