      'Responsive web design is the approach of creating websites that provide optimal viewing and interaction experiences across all devices and screen sizes. Coined by Ethan Marcotte in 2010, responsive design uses fluid grids, flexible images, and CSS media queries to adapt layouts to the viewing environment. Modern responsive design has evolved to include container queries, CSS clamp() for fluid typography, and intrinsic design patterns.\n\nKey responsive design techniques include mobile-first design methodology, CSS Grid and Flexbox for adaptive layouts, media queries for breakpoint-specific adjustments, viewport units (vw, vh, dvh) for proportional sizing, responsive images with srcset and the picture element, and fluid typography using clamp(). Container queries, a recent CSS addition, allow components to respond to their parent container size rather than the viewport, enabling truly portable responsive components.\n\nModern responsive design also encompasses responsive tables, touch-friendly interaction targets (minimum 44x44px), responsive navigation patterns (hamburger menus, bottom tabs), and performance considerations like serving appropriately sized images. Testing across real devices and screen sizes, using browser DevTools device emulation, and tools like BrowserStack ensures consistent experiences.',
