      'Progressive Web Apps (PWAs) are web applications that use modern web technologies to deliver app-like experiences through the browser. PWAs combine the reach of the web with the capabilities of native apps, including offline functionality, push notifications, home screen installation, and background sync. Google, Microsoft, and Apple all support PWA standards, with over 1 billion PWA installations across the web.\n\nPWAs are built on three core technologies: Service Workers for offline caching and background processing, Web App Manifest for installability and app-like appearance, and HTTPS for secure delivery. Workbox, developed by Google, simplifies service worker implementation with pre-built caching strategies (Cache First, Network First, Stale While Revalidate). The Cache API stores assets and API responses for offline access.\n\nModern PWA capabilities have expanded significantly with the Project Fugu initiative bringing native-like features to the web: File System Access API, Web Bluetooth, Web USB, Contact Picker, Badging API, and Web Share API. PWAs can be distributed through the Google Play Store and Microsoft Store, blurring the line between web and native applications. Companies like Twitter, Pinterest, Starbucks, and Uber use PWAs to reach users across platforms with a single codebase.',
