      'Single Page Applications (SPAs) are web applications that load a single HTML page and dynamically update content as the user interacts with the app, without requiring full page reloads. SPAs use client-side routing and JavaScript to render different views, providing smooth transitions and app-like responsiveness. React, Vue, Angular, and Svelte are the primary frameworks for building SPAs.\n\nSPAs communicate with backend services via REST APIs or GraphQL to fetch and update data asynchronously. Client-side state management using tools like Redux, Pinia, or Zustand maintains application state across views. Client-side routing libraries like React Router and Vue Router manage URL navigation and browser history integration. Code splitting and lazy loading ensure initial bundle sizes remain manageable despite the entire application running in the browser.\n\nModern SPA development addresses historical challenges through techniques like pre-rendering for SEO, skeleton screens and loading states for perceived performance, Service Workers for offline capability, and proper error boundaries for graceful degradation. The evolution toward hybrid approaches with frameworks like Next.js and Nuxt.js combines SPA interactivity with server-side rendering for improved SEO and initial load performance.',
