      'Static Site Generation (SSG) is the technique of pre-rendering web pages as static HTML files at build time rather than on each request. SSG delivers the fastest possible page loads by serving pre-built HTML from CDNs without server processing. Popular SSG frameworks include Next.js, Gatsby, Hugo, Astro, Eleventy, and Nuxt.js, each offering different approaches to static generation.\n\nAstro has emerged as a leading SSG framework with its islands architecture that generates zero JavaScript by default and selectively hydrates interactive components. Next.js supports hybrid approaches combining SSG, SSR, and ISR (Incremental Static Regeneration) within a single application. ISR enables on-demand page regeneration without full rebuilds, solving the freshness challenge of static sites for content-heavy applications.\n\nSSG is ideal for content-driven websites, documentation sites, marketing pages, blogs, and e-commerce product catalogs where content changes infrequently. The Jamstack architecture (JavaScript, APIs, Markup) pairs SSG with headless CMSs like Contentful, Sanity, and Strapi for content management, and serverless functions for dynamic features. CDN deployment ensures global distribution with sub-100ms response times.',
