      'Web accessibility (a11y) is the practice of designing and developing websites that can be used by everyone, including people with disabilities such as visual, auditory, motor, and cognitive impairments. The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.2, published by the W3C, provide the international standard with three conformance levels: A, AA (the most commonly required level), and AAA. Legal requirements like the ADA in the US, EAA in Europe, and AODA in Canada mandate web accessibility.\n\nAccessibility implementation includes semantic HTML structure, ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) attributes for complex widgets, keyboard navigation support, sufficient color contrast ratios (4.5:1 for normal text), focus management, screen reader compatibility, alternative text for images, captions for video, and skip navigation links. Automated testing tools like axe-core, Lighthouse, and WAVE catch approximately 30% of accessibility issues, while manual testing with screen readers (NVDA, VoiceOver, JAWS) and keyboard-only navigation are essential for comprehensive coverage.\n\nModern component libraries like Radix UI, Headless UI, and React Aria provide accessible-by-default primitives that handle complex accessibility patterns for dialogs, menus, comboboxes, and other interactive widgets. The overlay and remediation approach, used by accessibility overlay companies, is widely considered insufficient and should be replaced with native accessibility implementation.',
