      'Cross-browser compatibility is the practice of ensuring web applications function consistently and look correct across different web browsers and their versions. Despite increasing standards compliance, differences in rendering engines (Blink in Chrome/Edge, Gecko in Firefox, WebKit in Safari) still cause inconsistencies in CSS rendering, JavaScript API support, and HTML element behavior. Safari on iOS is often the most challenging browser due to WebKit restrictions and delayed feature adoption.\n\nModern cross-browser development involves using feature detection with Modernizr or CSS @supports, progressive enhancement to build from a baseline experience, polyfills for missing browser features, and transpilation with Babel to compile modern JavaScript to compatible versions. CSS vendor prefixes, managed through Autoprefixer, handle proprietary CSS implementations. The Can I Use database is the essential reference for checking feature support across browsers.\n\nTesting strategies include BrowserStack and Sauce Labs for cloud-based cross-browser testing, Playwright for automated cross-browser testing across Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit engines, and manual testing on real devices for mobile browsers. CSS reset or normalize stylesheets establish consistent baseline styles. Understanding the differences between browser developer tools helps diagnose browser-specific rendering issues.',
