      'Web performance optimization is the practice of improving the speed, responsiveness, and efficiency of web applications. Core Web Vitals—Largest Contentful Paint (LCP), Interaction to Next Paint (INP), and Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS)—are Google ranking factors and the primary metrics for measuring user experience. Optimizing these metrics directly impacts SEO rankings, conversion rates, and user satisfaction.\n\nPerformance optimization spans the entire stack: frontend techniques include code splitting, lazy loading, image optimization (WebP/AVIF, responsive images, lazy loading), CSS and JavaScript minification, tree shaking, critical CSS extraction, and font optimization (font-display: swap, subset fonts). Network optimizations include CDN deployment, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, resource hints (preload, prefetch, preconnect), compression (Brotli, gzip), and caching strategies with Cache-Control headers.\n\nServer-side optimizations include database query optimization, server-side caching with Redis or Varnish, edge computing for reduced latency, efficient serialization, and connection pooling. Monitoring tools like Lighthouse, WebPageTest, Chrome DevTools Performance panel, and real user monitoring (RUM) platforms like SpeedCurve and web-vitals library provide the data needed to identify and prioritize performance bottlenecks.',
